## ⚙️ Step-by-Step Configuration

### R1 — Interface Setup

```ios
enable
configure terminal
hostname R1

! Inside interface (LAN)
interface fastEthernet 0/0
 ip address 10.0.0.1 255.255.255.0
 ip nat inside
 no shutdown
 exit

! Outside interface (toward ISP/internet)
interface fastEthernet 0/1
 ip address 203.0.113.1 255.255.255.252
 ip nat outside
 no shutdown
 exit
```

> **Critical step:** You must define which interface is `inside` and which is `outside` before NAT will work. Traffic flows from inside → outside and gets translated.

### Default Route to ISP

```ios
ip route 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 203.0.113.2
```

---

### Part A — Static NAT

**Goal:** Map PC1's private IP (10.0.0.10) permanently to one public IP (203.0.113.5). Useful for servers that need a consistent public address.

```ios
! Static NAT — one-to-one permanent mapping
ip nat inside source static 10.0.0.10 203.0.113.5
```

**Test:** PC1 pings 8.8.8.8 — the source IP in the packet leaving Fa0/1 will be `203.0.113.5`.

---

### Part B — Dynamic NAT

**Goal:** Map inside hosts to a pool of public IPs on a first-come, first-served basis.

First, remove the static NAT entry:
```ios
no ip nat inside source static 10.0.0.10 203.0.113.5
```

Define the public IP pool:
```ios
ip nat pool PUBLIC_POOL 203.0.113.5 203.0.113.8 netmask 255.255.255.0
```

Define which inside hosts are eligible (ACL):
```ios
ip access-list standard NAT_HOSTS
 permit 10.0.0.0 0.0.0.255
 exit
```

Bind the ACL to the pool:
```ios
ip nat inside source list NAT_HOSTS pool PUBLIC_POOL
```

> **Limitation:** Dynamic NAT requires one public IP per active host. If you have 3 PCs and only 2 pool addresses, the third host gets no translation until one frees up.

---

### Part C — PAT (Port Address Translation / Overload)

**Goal:** Allow all inside hosts to share a single public IP using unique port numbers. This is how home routers work — one public IP for many devices.

Remove dynamic NAT first:
```ios
no ip nat inside source list NAT_HOSTS pool PUBLIC_POOL
no ip nat pool PUBLIC_POOL 203.0.113.5 203.0.113.8 netmask 255.255.255.0
```

Configure PAT using the outside interface IP:
```ios
! Reuse the same ACL (NAT_HOSTS already defines eligible hosts)
ip nat inside source list NAT_HOSTS interface fastEthernet 0/1 overload
```

> **`overload`** is the keyword that enables PAT. The router uses unique source port numbers to track each session, allowing thousands of hosts to share one public IP simultaneously.

