## 💡 NAT Types Quick Reference

| Type | Mapping | Use Case |
|------|---------|----------|
| Static NAT | 1 private → 1 public (permanent) | Internal servers needing a fixed public IP |
| Dynamic NAT | Many private → pool of public (temporary) | Orgs with multiple public IPs |
| PAT (overload) | Many private → 1 public (port-based) | Home/small office — most common |

### NAT Terminology
| Term | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| Inside local | Private IP of the host (before translation) |
| Inside global | Public IP assigned to the host (after translation) |
| Outside local | Destination IP as seen from inside |
| Outside global | Destination IP as seen from outside |

### Key Commands Summary
```ios
ip nat inside                                        ! Tag interface as inside
ip nat outside                                       ! Tag interface as outside
ip nat inside source static <private> <public>       ! Static NAT
ip nat pool <name> <start-ip> <end-ip> netmask <mask> ! Define pool
ip nat inside source list <acl> pool <name>          ! Dynamic NAT
ip nat inside source list <acl> interface <int> overload ! PAT
```
